 Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Ste","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["French: derivative of the ancient Germanic personal name <i>Sugo</i>, a short form of compound names beginnig with <i>Sug-</i>.","German: possibly of French origin (see 1 above). It is found in the central part of northern Germany.","Chinese: variant of   Xue  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Xue","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Chinese Hong, Jian, Hua, Liang, Wei, Yuan, Biao, Chun, Fei, Lixin, Ming, Qi, Min, Tian, Yiming.  Vietnamese Lan, Hao, Huan.","Chinese: Mandarin form of the surname 薛, originally denoting a ‘type of grass’ in ancient Chinese: (i) from Xue (薛), the name of an ancient state (originally located in Shandong province) dating back to the Xia dynasty (2070–1600  BC ). After it was annexed by the state of Chu during the Western Zhou dynasty (1046–771  BC ), the name of the state was adopted as a surname. (ii) from the placename Xue (薛), the name of a fief (located in Shandong province) granted to Meng Chang Jun (Lord Meng Chang), a famous prince of the state of Qi, known as one of “the four princes during the Warring States period (475–221  BC )”. (iii) adopted as the surname by the Chi Gan (叱干) family from the Xianbei ethnic group in northern China during the Northern Wei dynasty (386–534  AD ). (iv) borne by descendants of Xue Huai Yi (薛懷義), a famous general of the Tang dynasty (618–907  AD )."]}]},{"name":"Marie","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   Maria .  When first introduced to England in the Middle Ages, it was Angliciz